04181nam a22006375i 9780292735408DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212011txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2011005491  a97802927354087 a10.7560/7268712doi  a(DE-B1597)587549  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aBL1590.G66bF67 2011 7aREL0690002bisacsh04a295/.51 aForrest, S. K. Mendoza, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWitches, Whores, and Sorcerers :bThe Concept of Evil in Early Iran /cS. K. Mendoza Forrest. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2011  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tThe avesta and its translation -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter one. The Study of an Ancient Tradition -- tChapter tWo. The Iranians and Their Literature -- tChapter 3 Magic and the Magi -- tChapter Four. General Concepts of Evil in the Avesta -- tChapter Five. “Naturally” Occurring Evils -- tChapter six. Sorcerers, Witches, Whores, and Menstruating Women -- tChapter seven. The Evil Eye, Corpse- Abusing Criminals, Demon Worshippers, and Friends -- tChapter eight. Exorcistic and Apotropaic Rituals -- tChapter nine. Structure of Avestan Incantations -- tChapter ten. Uses for Avestan Incantations -- tChapter eleven. Exorcisms -- tChapter twelve. Conclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEarly Iranians believed evil had to have a source outside of God, which led to the concept of an entity as powerful and utterly evil as God is potent and good. These two forces, good and evil, which have always vied for superiority, needed helpers in this struggle. According to the Zoroastrians, every entity had to take sides, from the cosmic level to the microcosmic self. One of the results of this battle was that certain humans were thought to side with evil. Who were these allies of that great Evil Spirit? Women were inordinately singled out. Male healers were forbidden to deal with female health disorders because of the fear of the polluting power of feminine blood. Female healers, midwives, and shamans were among those who were accused of collaborating with the Evil Spirit, because they healed women. Men who worked to prepare the dead were also suspected of secret evil. Evil even showed up as animals such as frogs, snakes, and bugs of all sorts, which scuttled to the command of their wicked masters. This first comprehensive study of the concept of evil in early Iran uncovers details of the Iranian struggle against witchcraft, sorcery, and other "evils," beginning with their earliest texts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aGood and evilxReligious aspectsxZoroastrianism. 7aRELIGION / Zoroastrianism.2bisacsh1 aSkjaervø, Prods Oktor.1 aSkjærvø, Prods Oktor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292735408423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292735408/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK